description.text:
A collection of things I needed when doing some upgrades to my Robo3D R1+ printer.

ScrewHolder - Is a plastic nut for the top M6 screw used on the Smart XXL LCD case
Spacer - Is a tapered washer/spacer for the side screw used on the Smart XXL LCD case
RaspberryPi3 - Sled for mounting a Raspberry Pi in the base using double sided tape
SainSmart2Relay - Sled for mounting SainSmart 2 Relay board using double sided tape

Printer Brand:

Robo 3D

Printer:

R1 ABS + PLA Model

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

25%

ScrewHolder:
Use a M6 tap to thread the ScrewHolder which is installed on the under side of the Robo. It will be pretty obvious how it goes. DO NOT over tighten, it is plastic and the threads will strip.

Spacer:
Tapered end towards printer, I sized it to provide just enough clearance for the LCD case without it you would have to leave the screw loose because of the gap between the printer top and case tab.

Raspberry Pi 3 Sled:
Use M2.5 tap to thread the holes for M2.5x6 Nylon screw to hold Pi to sled. Double sided tape on bottom to attach to Robo base.

SainSmart 2-Relay Sled:
Use M3 tap to thread the holes for M3 Nylon screw to hold Relay board to sled. Double sided tape on bottom to attach to Robo base.
Used OpenSCAD, source provided.

description.text:
This plotclock can write the time, the weather, pollen data and when the bus will depart from DTU, Lyngby, Denmark. Either by sending a twitter with @mekatronik2016 or timebased.
We have created codes for a NodeMCU board to run the plot clock. The arms are run by three servomotors, the paper roll is run by one stepper motor.
We've designed this plot clock during the course 41030 "Mechatronics Design" at the Danish Technical University.

Rafts:

No
Glue some parts together after laser cutting, leave out some parts, so that mechanical parts can be changed.
We first designed the frame, and after that it was easier to design the case

I really liked Zensou's edited mesh family of the popular fennec fox model. They really show a lot more character and movement then my original.
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:859232

Those models, like the original, print superbly, but only if you have your printer tuned perfectly to use support materiel. This derivative aims to help those who's printer is incapable of using support materiel, yet still want a playful-looking fennec in their hands.

The nature of a plated items like this also allows you to print much larger versions of the original without getting a bigger printer.

You are still encouraged to use support materiel to support the relatively steep overhangs around the paws. Even with a 45deg overhang tolerance set in your slicer, the amount of support material required is minimal (see screenshot above). This should allow anyone to print their own animated fennec fox (kit).

I did the same to my original fennec fox model soon after it was published a few years ago.
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:20748

All that's required after printing is some super glue, and maybe a hobby knife.

Printing with a brim (first layer or so extends out slightly to insure full bed adhesion) is also recommended to avoid any unsightly gaps in your finished print due to warping.

After printing all the parts, apply a generous amount of CA or super glue to the split body and tail (sides that face the print bed). Once dry, use the same glue again to bond the tail to the body. Allow time for the glue to cure before doing the final touch ups.

Sanding the flat faces before gluing also ensures a lasting bond.

description.text:
This Y bracket for a prusamendel can (also) be used if you want or need your belt to run very close to your stepper. It is clipped onto your frame then bolted in and secured by the washers so you don't need to take your frame apart to get it on and off.
My steppers have machined pulleys fixed on them with a length of 14.5mm, but the teeth only go untill 10,5 mm.The pulleys have a diameter of 9.7mm with 11 teeth and a 3mm pitch. when your diameter is much bigger the belt cannot be so close to the stepper because it will not have enough clearance.

You can use this with a nut less than the standard design. I have the following on the rod: a nut, small washer, Y bracket, small washer, big washer, small washer, bearings, small washer, big washer, nut. 
To avoid a collision with my bottom print plate I have cut a bit out of the plate as you can see on the picture taken from the bottom of the reprap.
I have uploaded an stl file both with and without rounded edges. furthermore an inventor file. My bracket was printed on a commercial machine with a second extruder for the support material.

description.text: This is XYZ Workshop's winning entry into the MyMiniFactory chess and Pen design competition. The design is loosely based on a Bauhaus Style Chess set. We were interested in blending the simple strong geometric forms of the chess pieces with nature. The chess pieces allows nature lovers to integrate their favorite succulents or herbs into their game play. Each Chess piece can be planted with specific herbs or succulents to give them a level of individuality and personality. This also allows the player to assign unique textures, colors and smell to the pieces. Use some Corsican Mint to bring some minty freshness into you game, or perhaps a series of hard wearing cacti if you don't have a green thumb. We have also included a printable/portable chess board skin, measuring only 0.6mm thick. Printing four of these allows the player to turn any flat surface into their chessboard. Make this Green Chess set a feature in your garden, or bring the garden into your living room. If you like our designs please follow us at http://www.facebook.com/xyzworkshop

title: Cutting Compass for Drill Press/Hand Drill

description.text:
In the need of cutting a round hole (really round!) into a piece of polystyrene foam (in europe we call it styropor), this tool was designed. Whit it, it is possible to cut a round hole (guided by the 4mm drill) into any foam-like (or other soft...) material.
It was designed for minimal material use and printing time (made mine on a prusa with a 0.35mm nozzle within less than 15mins.

CAUTION!
This can be an extremely dangerous tool if you don't handle it with care. Please make sure you only hit the button of your drill if your fingers are in a safe distance from the blade! All you need except the printed parts is a 4mm drill bit, a piece of M4 threaded rod or a long M4 screw and some M4 nuts. I took the stuff I had lying around in my toolshop... Assemble as on sketch... You can change the diameter of the hole easily by unscrewing the blade or the drill. If you are going to use it with soft materials, you might want to print a centering disk too. Glue it onto your workpiece (hotglue is fine, double sided tape will do the job too...) to prevent the drill bit from breaking out too much. Hint:
I used a wing nut on the drill bit side to be able to change the cutting diameter by hand.

comments.text: The center-plate can be used as a glue-on tool to keep the drill in place if you use a really soft material like polystyrene foam, where the drill would eat too much material around its diameter. I glued it on with hotglue.

This is an IoT roll printer that can connect to IBM Bluemix (Node red) to receive information. It can write the time, weather, pollen numbers and tweets.
It uses 3 servo motors to control the pen that writes and a stepper motor to wind up the paper roll. The housing is made from laser cut acrylic and plywood.

The plotter itself is a modified version of the Plotclock by joo.

We are six people from Technical University of Denmark and we designed it as a part of the course Mechatronics Design (41030).
We designed the thing in PTC Creo Parametrics, by importing the original Plotclock design by Joo. Afterwards we added the casing and custom parts for securing paper roll and the other parts.

Everything else than the electronics is laser cut in 3mm plywood and acrylic. The electronics can be bought online.

Parts used:

  • NodeMCU (esp8266)
  • 3x Servo motors
  • Sharp 1A51HR photo interrupter
  • Stepper motor 45x45mm (taken from a printer)
  • Power supply with 5v output (taken from another electronics device)
  • EasyDriver (Stepper motor driver)
  • Receipt roll
  • Acrylic 3mm - approximately A3 size
  • Plywood 3mm - 450 x 140mm

The case is assembled first and glued together. All the other parts are “plug and play”.

Two lids can be removed for easy access to electronics and for change of the receipt roll.

It might be necessary to do a little bit of grinding, due to press fit.

With lids removed

When connected to power and the internet, it will show time and weather at specific times. This is programmed in Node Red. It is also possible to tweet to the printer.

Le mini patator présenté dans la vidéo d'impression 3D sur la chaîne YouTube ExperimentBoy !
Vous pouvez télécharger les 3 parties à imprimer sur un seul fichier, ou séparément en cas de besoin :)
Les deux trous sur les côté sont prévus pour un allumeur piezoélectrique de briquet (le truc noir qui fait clic clic sur certains briquets). Il suffit de relier le fil sortant du piezo dans un trou, et de relier un fil sur la partie métallique pour l'insérer dans l'autre, et avec un écart correct il se formera une étincelle entre les fils.
Mettez ensuite un projectile à l'entrée du canon (près de la chambre) qui le bouche complètement sans être en force, puis un PETIT PEU de gaz de briquet à l'arrière. À l'échelle de base, 1 à 2s de pression sur un briquet suffisent pour avoir de bonnes proportions.
À échelle 150% (comme présenté dans la vidéo), c'est environ 4-5s.

Soyez prudents je ne serai pas responsable des dégâts ou blessures potentiellement engendrés, cela reste un jouet ! Amusez-vous bien ! :)

This model is a Solidworks redesign / remix of IE_z_motor_mount_10mm_longer_25mm.

  • filler plates (the STL is 0,3mm thick)

This is the first iteration of a design that I'm working on for making a printable wallet that fits comfortably in your pocket but gives similar function to it's leather counterparts. It definitely isn't the last version of this file and I'm working on adding on an extra flap for holding notes in a separate compartment that gives easy, but secure access.

If you want to make one of these you need some 3 - 4mm shock cord - less than a metre would be fine. Ideally the smaller diameter cord would be better as it seems to work with the hook.

Build Advice
Start feeding the cord from the bottom - the side that doesn't have the cord hook - and underside - the side with less cut out of it - and keep working it through with both plates aligned until you get all the way around to the opposite side, then tie them together. Tension according to how many cards you want in it - you want it fairly tight to ensure the retaining loop stays secure and then tie the loose ends using a reef knot. To close the wallet lift the upper loop over the hook and away you go.

title: Full crossbracing for Prusa simplified Mendel

description.text:
AKA sildenafil for Prusa Mendel, part of the mythic quest for less vibrations and bending, a more rigid frame that can work with more tensioned belts. Also check: Y motor mount torsion box for Prusa simplified Mendel http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:11017
Smooth rod / shaft collar from a drilled out M8 nut http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:11068 Selis Mendel features a plywood or acrylic plate there, Prusa Mendel has nothing. I am too lazy to cut plywood right now, so here it is. Inspired by Lateral support for Prusa by Miro87043 http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:14606 , this solution is, I believe, more comprehensive with a full triangulation, while staying out of the way and keeping the filament needs reasonable: about 40 grams for both side pieces, and 28.5 grams for the top assembly. This part has been thought as an unobtrusive upgrade: no need to dismantle your pyramid amid much fear and loathing, the thing has brackets to bolt it over the existing studding. This comes at the cost of slightly more filament and just a few bolts. The top part has some residual flexibility along the X axis. This might help with dampening, or not. Alternatively the part can be printed as a box, or massive by editing the dxf and re-exporting the stl from openscad. The code is a huge mess, in a big need of cleanup and parametrization. Update 20120109: Thanks to http://www.thingiverse.com/Justblair 's excellent work, a finalized version has been uploaded (all.stl and the openscad revised files).

print 1x top_n_bracket.stl and 1x sides.stl, or 1x all.stl In addition to the mentioned nuts and bolts, you will need to cut some M8 studding: 1x300 mm, and 2 x 190 mm. Use nylock nuts, cyanoacrylate glue or double nuts. Somebody should try recording and doing FFT analysis on the vibrations of frames with or without bracing at differents speeds. A microphone or a piezo should be suitable... Empirically, there IS a significant difference. The side brackets can also be used to cross-brace the machine's base. you will need 2x same side. Discussion on the reprap forums: http://forums.reprap.org/read.php?151,112816
